size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e the purpose of public service </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">broadcasting</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span><a name="a2"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a multitude of definitions and descriptions of public service broadcasting. The BBC's fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rst Director General Lord Reith</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> said that the responsibility of public service broadcasting was to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">"carry into the greatest number of homes everything that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">was best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement; and to avoid whatever was or might be hurtful".</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><a name="n3"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In 2000, the Independent Television Commission defined it as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">"all things to all people at least some of the time … with a strong em</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">phasis on extending public knowledge, tastes and interests"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2003, the concept of public service broadcasting was enshrined in the Communications Act</span><a name="n5"></a><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which defined the public service remit for Channels 3 and 5</span><a name="n6"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as "</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the provision of a range of high qual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ity and diverse programming".</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the years, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in various speeches and report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, regulators and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> government have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> extended this to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cover </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">content that the market does not sufficiently provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">de’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emphasise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the BBC’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reputation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for high standards and quality of services and programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in raising the industry benchmark and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“…in keeping the rest of the industry honest”.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hen the House of Lords Communications C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ttee looked at this issue in 2009, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> number of witnesses added </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> further distinguishing characteristic of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public service broadcasting: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">universality of access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> According to Mark Thompson, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the-then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBC Director General, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">"one of the … founding elements of public service broadcasting is an idea of a universal service."</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agree with this statement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva will refrain from adding to the growing literature by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">attempt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a new definition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of public service broadcasting,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e recognise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">universality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a defining characteristic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by which we mean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> content</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> accessible to everyone – on all platforms and free at the point of consumption.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed in the </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">current</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva will restrict our evidence in discussing the BBC’s 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public purpose, namely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the promotion of emerging communications technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Charter and Agreement require the Trust </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to ensure that the BBC helps to deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services. In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion, the Agreement has required the BBC to take a leading role in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">switchover from analogue to digital television…by supporting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Digital UK, by improving the technical infrastructure and by providing information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and support to audiences. These goals wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l in part be achieved through the BBC’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">activities in promoting its other five Public Purposes, in particular by the production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and promotion of high-quality digital content and services that encourage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">audiences to obtain the maximum benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the oppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tunities available. The BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is committed to achieving these aims in the most cost-effective way possible.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no doubt that, over this current Charter period, the BBC has provided engaging digital </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">content and services available on a wide range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">digital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">platforms and devices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as digital television, digital radio,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mobile devices and the internet.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s cross-platform innovative reporting and broadcasting of the 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Olympics is testament to this. For example, u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p to 24 simultaneous live eve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts were available to satellite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and cable homes via Red Button</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with Freeview homes getting up to two extra channels in S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tandard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efinition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and one in H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">igh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efinition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Over twenty four million people (42% of the UK population) watched at least 15 minutes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> coverage on the BBC Red Button.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Meanwhile,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is to the benefit of the UK citizens, audiences and Licence Fee payers that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freeview,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> YouView and BBC iplayer go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from strength to strength. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only 12 months </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">since TV Switchover </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was completed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acros</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the transmission contractor for all UK terrestrial television services, Arqiva had the responsibility for implementing the switchover at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 1154 transmitters sites across the UK – part of a mammoth five-ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar £630m project. Every single site had to be re-engineered, each one an operational site requiring existing services to be ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intained right up to switchover.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Arqiva has no doubt that the BBC’s unwavering support for TV Switchover </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– including their role al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ongside ITV in establishing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freesat -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensured the project was a huge success. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We commend t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he BBC’s role in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">targeted assistance s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to help vulnerable group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s buy and install new equipment. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">advice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support for Digital UK’s marketing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and communications activity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vital in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">build</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> awareness of, and re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adiness for, digital switchover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva is proud to collaborate with the BBC, and others in the industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continue to deliver improvements to the UK-wide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">distribution of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public service content.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">announcement that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">five new sub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scription-free BBC HD channels, (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBC News HD, BBC Three HD, BBC Four HD, CBeebies HD and CBBC HD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - will launch by Christmas 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and will be offered to all digital television p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">latforms that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arry HD channels.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We agree with the BBC Trust that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s important </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Corporation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should continue to deliver and invest in emerging broadcasting and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">distribution technologies - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including red button, HD, IPTV, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mobile</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public value to do so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the last few years the radio industry and Arqiva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have invested in building national and local DAB digital radio coverage across the UK.  This project will continue over the next two years with the launch of new local DAB stations and the further expansion of national BBC and commercial DAB coverage. Ove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r 25 million people in the UK now listen to digital radio each week, mostly on DAB, but also online via a computer, tablet or mobile phone or via digital TV. Over 44% of UK homes have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a DAB digital radio and over 41</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% of new cars have digital radio fitted a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s standard</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Listeners who have good coverage love digital radio and enjoy the choice of stations, digital sound quality, ease of tuning and the availability of track and artist information. The radio industry is working with government to expand DAB cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">age to maximise the number of people who can receive and enjoy digital radio, whilst a 3-year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government/Industry Digital Radio Action Plan has recently completed the necessary planning for a potential future consumer-led digital switchover. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva notes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the BBC Trust pledged in March 2013 that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“…The BBC should enhance its national DAB coverage and work with Government and industry to prepare for any potential radio switchover by putting together plans to build out infrastructure for local DAB in lin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e with the joint Memorandum of Understanding.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pleased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the BBC are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> actively building </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">162 additional DAB transmitters to extend national BBC DAB coverage to above 97%. The programme of work starts this year</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to expand coverage of national</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> BBC DAB, and will also strengthen coverage in some major cities and conurbations.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransmitters will be added at a rate of more than three every two weeks between now and Christmas 2015. The fourth-phase of the roll-out will bring network BBC radio on DAB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to an extra 2.5m people and improve coverage for millions of others.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When considering a Radio Switchover, the DCMS Strategy document, published July 2013 says “….</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">It is important that the transition to digital is consumer-led and carefully managed…To ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e there is clarity around the longer-term future of analogue and digital radio, we are committed to making a decision in-principle on a radio switchover at the end of this year.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Arqiva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the BBC, major commercial radio stations, including Bauer, Global a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd RadioCentre, who represent National and local stations accounting for over 96% of radio listening, are in support of a radio switchover decision, which means certainty for the radio industry and better coverage and choice for listeners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In achieving Rad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">io Switchover it is essential that the BBC continues to lead the way in building out DAB coverage both for national and local services.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believes the public purposes in the current Charter have broadly served audiences, citizens and licence fee payers well. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We note</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in discussing the 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Public Purpose - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the BBC Trust believes the BBC should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“…w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ork in partnership with other organisati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ons to help all audiences understand and adopt emerging communications technologies and services. The BBC should work with other UK bodies to end the ‘digital divide’ between those who enjoy the benefits of digital technologies and those outside that group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rqiva agree with this statement – and believe the BBC has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibility to continue this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">throughout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the next Charter period.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, as well as bringing exciting new benefits, new forms of communication and emerging platforms bring new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunities for misuse.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n recent years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emerging commercial ‘new media’ platforms and social networking, in a largely unregulated space, have exposed young people to a range of new dangers – from the exposure to ‘adult content’, to the phenomena of ‘cyb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erbullying’, ‘grooming’, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sexting’, ‘self-harm’, gaming, gambling, as well as illegal downloading and file sharing, or online fraud.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva believes that children and young people should be able to enjoy the benefits of digital technology and the internet,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> whilst having the right to be safe online. Indeed, the commitment to ensure child safety online is a matter of grave importance – and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be a shared responsibility between parents, businesses and the wider communications industry including ISPs, web p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ublishers, WiFi providers and government.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hen it comes to online safety, we also believe that all the public service broadcasters should play a key role in educating the public. The BBC should be praised for regularly commissioning innovative, mu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lti-platform content which insp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ires and educates audiences. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indeed, the BBC's content and services are perhaps the most powerful means to drive adoption as well as to educate the public as to the risks of emerging technologies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC is a trusted guide t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o the digital world for the inexperienced or unsure, a safe place to be for the young, a reliable and accurate on-air and online source for the information seeker, and a challenging and involving partner for the more advanced user. Ultimately, ‘online safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty’ should be regarded as an important plank of the BBC’s commitment to support the media literacy of all its audience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When considering the scope, scale and remit at the last Charter Review, Arqiva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> notes that “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he vast majority of those wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o gave oral or written evidence…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were united in wanting to see a strong BBC. Even the BBC's </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">major competitors spoke of its value.”</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, at the last Charter Review, there was a strong political consensus on th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e BBC's importance, with the-then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government recognising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “…the enormous contribution that the BBC has made to British life and culture, both at home and abroad.”</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t would be a great loss if this c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onsensus was undermined</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> majority of British people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">want to see the BBCs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contribution m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aintained into the digital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the cornerstone of broadcasting in the United Kingdom and is respected across the world. BBC news and current affairs, on television, radio and online are known for their accuracy and impartiality. The BBC brand is respected abroad and the BBC World Servic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e is praised as an objective international radio broadcaster in almost every country surveyed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva notes that the BBC has always offered a wide selection of programming and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we believe this should continue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The BBC should continue to provide a full rang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of programmes and not be confined to programmes not provided by other broadcasters. In short the BBC should strive to serve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> licence fee payers across the whole of the United Kingdom and provide them with high quality programmes and services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? </span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he BBC should strive to serve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> licence fee payers across the whole of the United Kingdom and provide them with high quality programmes and services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hat balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva has no view</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no view</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva notes that Tony Hall has stated “innovation has been a part of the BBC from its very foundation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. You have to refresh, you have to regenerate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ree. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">He has an exciting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vision for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBC iPlayer to be “the best online TV service in the world”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and for a re-invented iPlayer, BBC Store, Playlister, Open Minds “…to be a bold era of BBC innovation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We agree these are all important innovations – but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ob</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">serve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> broadband is still not universally-available across the UK, and – unlike Freeview – is not free at the point of consumption.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As Ofcom notes in its spectrum strategy, IPTV won’t be a substitute for linear terrestrial broadcast until after 2030. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing the current Charter period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the success of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freeview, has been a key driver in the take up of digital </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">television. Indeed DTT is the cornerstone of UK broadcasting, delivering unique range of economic and social benefits through universally available,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> free to air television. The popularity of Freeview at the heart of DTT creates the scale and reach to drive competition and support consumer choice. It attracts investment in high quality programmes which fuel our creative industries and help make the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a global leader in TV production. DTT is a simple proposition for viewers and the most efficient way to ensure public service programmes remain prominent, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">universally available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">free at the point of use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Freeview </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is the UK’s most popular TV platform, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tched in almost 20 million homes (75 per cent of all TV homes) and the sole television platform in almost 11 million homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Terrestrial t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elevision will continue to grow:-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The DTT platform (Freeview and YouView combined) is set to account for 40 per cent o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the country’s primary TV homes in 2020 (12 million)</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. DTT i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s highly valued by UK consumers and looks set to remain so in 2020 and beyond. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The platform is vital to the distribution of BBC content. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DTT broadcasts 95 per cent of the country’s most watched</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programmes</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subscription-free.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DTT delivers bigger audiences for public service channels than any other platform – accounting for 61 per cent of viewing among terrestrial viewers (44 per cent in cable satellite homes), helping sustain the PSBs’ an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nual programme-making investment of £3 billion. These mass audiences are also popular with advertisers and account for the lion’s share of £3.6 billion</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in revenues used by commercial channels such as ITV and Channel 4 to fund world-beating television cont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent. This successful economic model in turn plays a pivotal role in sustaining a world beating programme export industry worth over £1.4 billion</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DTT platform will also continue to develop as advances in technology are introduced and consumer behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evolves. Freeview HD and Freeview+ are now well established and popular. Extra HD channels are being launched during 2013/14 while smart TVs and YouView combine high-quality live programming delivered via DTT with access to catch-up and on-demand services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> via broadband. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These internet-based services are a complement to the broadcast channels which still account for the vast majority of viewing. The UK continues to watch live TV 90 per cent of the time</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As Ofcom notes in its spectrum strategy, IPTV won’t b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a substitute for linear terrestrial broadcast until after 2030. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important Freeview continues to evolve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to offer viewers extra features, including a growing line-up of HD channels, digital recording and connected technologies. Smart TVs and You Vi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ew are providing additional choice through catch-up and on-demand services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A platform-wide upgrade to the latest DVB-T2 technology would both enable additional HD services to be offered and also deliver even more efficient use of spectrum. As all DVB-T2 t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elevision displays are broadband-enabled, the platform upgrade would also help to drive a connected UK. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ext Charter period, the BBC must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have a continuing and vial role in innovating the platform.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On radio, as stated above: the BBC should continue to support the drive to a digital future for radio by continuing to invest in strong digital-only stations and by continuing to take the lead in building out coverage. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be funded beyond </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2016? </span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC has been funded by the Licence Fee since 1923 when the first wireless licence was issued. </span><a name="a21"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The licence fee has the advantages of being simple and straightforward. It is a generally well understood and accepted method of funding the BBC. Reven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ue created by the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icence fee is stable and secure -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more predicta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ble than other means of funding -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and allows for long term planning</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reliability of the licence fee as a funding source, coupled with the fact that it makes the BBC independent of commer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cial considerations, has enabled the BBC to develop the programming and services on which its reputation is based.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Arqiva believes the Licence Fee mechanism has served the BBC well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and should continue to do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is there a case for distributing funding for </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">public service content more widely beyond the BBC?</span><a name="a30"></a></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n this current Charter Period, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Licence Fee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, controversially,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to fund additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">non-BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ollowing the renegotiation of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">licence fee settlement in October 2010,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the BBC is now also responsible for S4C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was also required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to help with </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/making-it-easier-for-the-media-and-creative-industries-to-grow-while-protecting-the-interests-of-citizens/supporting-pages/creating-a-local-tv-framework-so-that-local-tv-services-can-be-set-up-across-the-uk"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Government's aim of establishing a Local TV network</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including making</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> up to £5 million per year over three</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">available from the TV Licence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to acquire local conte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> help support the continued existence of a plurality of news providers at all levels of the UK.”</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="a28"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC should offer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">engaging, high quality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">content, programmes and services available on a wide range of digital platforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to serve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> licence fee payers across the whole of the United Kingdom. Anything which redirects Licence Fee money to other rival broadcasters or purposes may serve to undermine the Corporation’s core output or objectives. </span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the years, there have been several pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">posals for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> competition for licence fee funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(so-called “contestable” public funding) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and suggested distribution via a "public servic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e fund", rather than by a stand-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alone body</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We are un-persuaded by either an ‘Arts Council of The Air’ or a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public Servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce Broadcasting Comm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ission’ that would coordinate dir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ect funding of public service o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bligations from the licence fee etc, or indeed any free-standing “Public Service Publisher” idea which would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commission and produce public service programmes directly to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number of broadcasters from funds provided by the licence fee or by general taxation. </span><a name="a31"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainly, more evidence is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required about whether advertising-funded broadcasters will cease to provide public service content and services and more evidence is required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about possible new public service providers, some internet based, who might have a claim on public funding for provision of public service content.</span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are not persuaded by either a contestable or a top-sliced licence fee. We are concerned that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would weaken the BBC's capability to produce a broad range of public broadcasting. There would no longer be one body accountable to the public for the use of the licence fee and this could weaken the public understanding of and engagement with PSB. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We beli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eve that the TV licence fee should – in principle - remain the BBC’s and warn that "top-slicing" the licence fee would undermine the BBC's accountability for use of the licence fee and weaken the link with the public. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What comparisons can be made with the</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> provision of public service content in other countries? </span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK benefits from a mixed ecology in public service broadcasters including the Licence Fee funded BBC and the commercial public service broadcasters. The BBC is held in high international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regard.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is no coincidence, since t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he BBC is the premiere example of public service intervention in broadcasting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK benefits from a strong BBC, independent of government, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specifics of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBC’s governance arrangements </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">framework for the BBC?</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva would welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government awarding the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a renewed 10 year Charter, providing certainty for the Corporation, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certainty for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the wider broadcasting, media, commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nications and technology sector, as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as the wider crea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tive economy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva believes the UK benefits from a strong BBC, independent of government. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is vital that the process for agreeing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">constitution of the BBC is open and transparent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Both Houses of Parliament must be able to have a full part in the Cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rter Review process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arqiva has no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">view on the constitutional arrangements of the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Such as the wireless cameras operated by the BBC and Sky </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">News, and the radio microphones used in virtually all television production and many West End shows.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Reith, Into the Wind 1949</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Communications Act 2003 – Section 264</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Speech by Michael Grade, ‘Building Public Value’ 29 June 2004; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">BBC Press Release</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">: Michael Grade resigns as BBC Chairman 28.11.06</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Lords Communications Committee Report: “Public service broadcasting: short-term crisis, long-term future?” (March 2009)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> BBC Trust documents – Purpose Remits March 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">BBC Blogs - Olympics: Red Button</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> - Tuesday 14 August 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofcom Press Release - New HD channels on terrestrial TV – 16 July 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Society of Motor Manufactu